Bug: linking libxul.so fails with "undefined reference to
`gfxShapedWord* gfxFont::GetShapedWord<unsigned char>(...)'" (called
from gfxTextRun.cpp's SetSpaceGlyph()). GetShapedWord is a member
template that is only ever defined in gfxFont.cpp (declared, not
defined, in gfxFont.h), so callers in other translation units --
such as gfxTextRun.cpp -- depend entirely on gfxFont.cpp emitting an
externally-linkable out-of-line copy of each specialization they use.

gfxFont.cpp already works around the equivalent problem for
SplitAndInitTextRun with explicit instantiations further up (see the
adjacent "to avoid libxul link failure" comment, from 2015). It never
extended that treatment to GetShapedWord itself, apparently because
older GCC reliably emitted it as a byproduct of instantiating
SplitAndInitTextRun (which calls GetShapedWord internally). Modern
GCC's more aggressive inlining at -Os, combined with --gc-sections,
drops that emitted-but-unreferenced-in-TU copy, leaving external
callers with nothing to link against.

Add the same explicit-instantiation treatment for GetShapedWord<uint8_t>
and GetShapedWord<char16_t> (the two types textrun code needs).
Index: gfx/thebes/gfxFont.cpp
--- a/gfx/thebes/gfxFont.cpp	Thu Jan 08 23:22:45 2015 -0500
+++ b/gfx/thebes/gfxFont.cpp	Sun Jul 12 12:14:50 2026 +0800
@@ -2801,6 +2801,32 @@
                              int32_t aRunScript,
                              bool aVertical);
 
+// Explicit instantiations of GetShapedWord, to avoid libxul link failure.
+// This template is only ever defined here, but is called externally (e.g.
+// from gfxTextRun.cpp); without an explicit instantiation, the compiler is
+// free to inline every in-TU use and never emit an externally-linkable
+// out-of-line copy.
+template gfxShapedWord*
+gfxFont::GetShapedWord(gfxContext *aContext,
+                       const uint8_t *aText,
+                       uint32_t aLength,
+                       uint32_t aHash,
+                       int32_t aRunScript,
